      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold text-navy-950 mb-6 leading-tight">Volleyball Jersey Materials Explained for Players and Coaches</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-10 leading-relaxed">The fabric in your volleyball jersey affects moisture control, range of motion, print quality, and long-term durability. Understanding the differences helps you order the right jersey for your program.</p>

      <div class="prose-custom">
        <h2>Why Fabric Choice Matters in Volleyball</h2>
        <p>Volleyball is a sport that demands extreme physical flexibility — overhead serves, lateral dives, explosive vertical jumps, and repetitive arm swings. Fabrics that restrict movement, hold moisture against the skin, or deteriorate after a few months of intensive training undermine player performance and create unnecessary replacement costs. Choosing the right material is not just about comfort; it directly affects how players perform.</p>

        <h2>100% Polyester: The Standard</h2>
        <p>The overwhelming majority of competitive volleyball jerseys — including most of our <a href="/volleyball-jerseys/">custom volleyball jerseys</a> — use 100% polyester fabric. Here is why it dominates the market:</p>
        <p><strong>Moisture wicking:</strong> Polyester does not absorb water the way cotton does. Instead, sweat moves from the skin through the fabric to the outer surface where it evaporates quickly. During a long tournament day, this keeps players significantly drier and more comfortable than natural fiber alternatives.</p>
        <p><strong>Sublimation compatibility:</strong> Dye-sublimation printing only works on polyester (and certain polyester blends). If you want full-color, edge-to-edge custom designs, polyester is the only viable fabric choice. Cotton and cotton blends produce dull, limited-color results and cannot support the vibrant designs that modern teams expect.</p>
        <p><strong>Shape retention:</strong> Polyester maintains its shape over time. It does not stretch out, shrink, or pill the way cotton does. A jersey that fits correctly on day one should still fit correctly after two years of regular washing.</p>
        <p><strong>Weight options:</strong> Lightweight polyester (100–140 GSM) is ideal for warm conditions and high-intensity play. Medium weight (150–180 GSM) is standard for most competitive programs and provides a balance of durability and breathability. Heavier weights are used for practice jerseys that need to withstand more aggressive handling.</p>

        <h2>Polyester-Spandex Blends</h2>
        <p>Adding spandex (also called elastane or Lycra) to polyester creates a fabric with elastic properties that polyester alone cannot provide. Common ratios are 88/12 (polyester/spandex) and 90/10. Here is what the spandex component adds:</p>
        <p><strong>4-way stretch:</strong> The fabric stretches in four directions — horizontal, vertical, and both diagonal axes. This is particularly valuable for defensive players who execute frequent floor movements, and for setters and liberos whose mechanics require extreme shoulder rotation.</p>
        <p><strong>Compression:</strong> Spandex blends can provide mild to moderate compression depending on the blend ratio and fabric weight. Some players find this beneficial for muscle support and recovery during long tournament days. Our <a href="/volleyball-compression-shirts/">volleyball compression shirts</a> use a higher spandex ratio for a more pronounced compression effect.</p>
        <p><strong>Form-fitting silhouette:</strong> Spandex blends tend to hug the body. This is standard for women's volleyball jerseys, especially at the competitive level, but is gaining popularity in men's volleyball as well. Players who prefer a looser silhouette should specify this when ordering.</p>

        <h2>Mesh Fabric Panels</h2>
        <p>Some volleyball jerseys incorporate open-weave mesh fabric in strategic locations — typically the sides, underarms, and back. Mesh panels dramatically increase air circulation in areas where heat accumulates during play. They are especially popular for summer tournaments and indoor gyms without adequate climate control.</p>
        <p>Mesh panels are available as an add-on to any of our standard jersey styles. The mesh areas can be in a contrasting team color or match the base jersey color for a more seamless appearance. Note that sublimation printing on mesh panels has slight limitations compared to solid-weave polyester, so designs in mesh areas are typically simpler.</p>

        <h2>Moisture-Wicking Technology</h2>
        <p>"Moisture-wicking" is often used as a general marketing term, but it describes a specific engineering process. The most effective moisture-wicking fabrics use micro-channel constructions — tiny pathways built into the fabric structure that draw sweat away from the skin via capillary action. Higher-end performance fabrics also incorporate antimicrobial treatments that prevent odor-causing bacteria from accumulating in the fibers, extending the freshness of the jersey between washes.</p>
        <p>All fabrics we use in our <a href="/sublimated-volleyball-jerseys/">sublimated volleyball jerseys</a> and game uniforms meet performance-grade moisture management standards. We do not use standard polyester that merely avoids absorbing water — we use fabrics with active moisture transport technology.</p>

        <h2>Care Requirements by Fabric Type</h2>
        <p>Proper care extends the life of any volleyball jersey significantly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Machine wash on a cool or warm cycle (not hot — heat degrades polyester fibers and can affect sublimated colors)</li>
          <li>Use a mild detergent without bleach or fabric softener (fabric softener clogs moisture-wicking channels)</li>
          <li>Air dry when possible — tumble drying on low is acceptable but avoid high heat settings</li>
          <li>Do not iron over sublimated designs</li>
          <li>Wash jerseys inside-out to preserve exterior print quality</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Fabric Considerations by Player Position</h2>
        <p>Different positions place different demands on jersey fabrics. Liberos and defensive specialists benefit most from stretch fabrics due to floor movement requirements. Setters may prefer lighter-weight jerseys that do not restrict overhead arm mechanics. Outside hitters and middles who focus on vertical play may find standard athletic-cut polyester jerseys perfectly adequate. For mixed teams, our standard polyester-spandex blend in an athletic cut serves most positions well without compromise.</p>
